title: For Sale:  Type 53 rifle (Chinese M44 - 7.62x54R)
postcontent:
For sale is a 1954 manufactured Type 53 carbine. This is the Chinese version of the venerable Soviet Model 44 (M44) carbine, which was a shorter version of the Mosin-Nagant battle rifle. It features an attached bayonet, and a 5-round magazine. All parts are original, although the bolt SN doesn't match the others. The non-matching is typical of these rifles. 

Unlike most other examples for sale, this rifle is NOT caked with cosmoline. This Chinese rifle is a wonderful shooter, and features a chrome-lined bore that is easier to clean than the Russian versions. That's particularly helpful if you're shooting corrosive ammunition. 

The steel has a nice, attractive patina and the stock is in decent (although clearly used) condition.

postcontent:
I have a Yugo Krinkov AK 47 in 7.62x39 that I am selling.  This is not one of the PAPs that you see everywhere.  This was built from a military kit on an American Nodak Spud receiver which has a side rail so that you could mount optics of your choice.  The barrel is 12.25" long and has a muzzle brake spot welded on that takes it to legal rifle length.  The front gas block is Krinkov with the integrated front sight. This is really handy and would be great as a truck gun or registered and made into a short barreled rifle.  It does a great job on pigs too!

title: For Trade:  Marlin Model 60 and Westernfield 87A
postcontent:
Hey all. I've got two .22 rifles for trade. These were a storage unit find. I've cleaned on them a little, but could use some more elbow grease. They appear to be in working order, if missing a part each.

First is a Marlin model 60. Synthetic "Dragunov"  style stock. Appears to have a stainless steel barrel. According to the serial # it was made in the early 80s. Missing interior magazine tube, although it does have the spring and follower. Someone threaded the barrel, although I have no idea to what dimensions. Trigger/bolt ect look to be in good working order. Just seems to missing the mag tube.

Second is a Westernfield model 87A. This is a store brand of the Savage model 87. They are known as gill guns due to their slotted receiver. Rifle is complete minus original charging handle. I have jury-rigged a new charging handle made of a small dowel. Neat design, the bolt will remain to the rear as long as the trigger is depressed, and close forward when the trigger is released. Search it on youtube to see what I mean. :] Bluing is worn, but rifle appears to be in good overall condition.

So there you have it. Two beater .22 rifles that need some time and love.

Interested in trading mostly. Trade value $200 for both rifles. Not really interested in cash as much as a cheap revolver or Mosin or something. I'm interested in just about anything, as long as its a Firearm.

Please call or text me at REDACTED if you're interested, and have a good day!

ARX100: Today’s Ultimate Tactical Rifle
The ARX100 was engineered with one purpose in mind: to be today’s best tactical semiauto rifle. It takes the concept of a modular rifle to futuristic levels, while maintaining an absolutely simple operation that make it ultra-reliable. With ambidextrous controls, easily-replaceable barrel and virtually endless possibilities for customization and accessorization, the ARX100 is adaptable to any firing scenario and is perfect for today’s most demanding tactical shooter.
Ultimate Reliability and Ease of Maintenance
The ARX100 features a constant contact/short-stroke gas piston system that makes it feed and fire under the most unforgiving conditions. The lightweight technopolymer receiver allows for reliable operation with virtually no lubricants. To make maintenance easy and trouble-free, this rifle has no pins and can be completely disassembled in a matter of seconds with no tools at all.
Ultimate Versatility
This rifle was designed to be completely ambidextrous, and all the critical controls on it may be operated right- or left-handed. These include the 2-position safety, the magazine release, the bolt release and charging handle and the case-ejection selector, which determines whether spent brass is ejected to the right or left. The flip-up backup sights that come standard on the ARX100 are also versatile, offering an easily-adjustable diopter system ranged from 100 to 800 yards. The barrel is also easily replaceable in seconds, making is possible to use different lengths and calibers without any tools required. Lastly, the folding stock is adjustable for length of pull at the touch of a button, using a simple and rugged telescopic construction.
Ultimate Accessorization
The possibilities for accessorization on the ARX100 are limited only by the user’s imagination. It comes out of the box with a full-length Picatinny rail on top, which is perfect for attaching a variety of optics and other sighting systems. It also has Picatinny rails on both sides of and under the fore-end, which offer countless possibilities for easily adding lighting systems and other tactical devices.

title: For Sale:   TEXAS RANGER 12 GA. LONG BARREL SINGLE SHOT
location: South Minneapolis, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Texas Ranger was a trade name used by Montgomery, Ward and Company of Chicago on shotguns made by J. Stevens Arms and Tool Company in the period 1900 to 1915.

Shotguns of this era may have Damascus, Twist or Laminated Steel barrels which are not considered safe with modern ammunition. Even if the gun has fluid steel barrels, the chambers may be shorter than today's 2 3/4" length shells. If using is contemplated, an evaluation by a competent gunsmith to determine barrel steel composition and chamber length is recommended. Modern 2 ¾” shells fired in a short chamber produces dangerously high pressures and can damage the gun and injure the shooter or bystanders. If deemed safe to use, only light field or target loads can be recommended.

Retail value would range from $50 to $125 depending on mechanical and bore condition and remaining original wood and metal finish.
